[0m[49m[39m  190, 196[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  191, 197[0m:[39m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[39m  192, 198[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  193, 199[0m:[39m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[39m  194, 200[0m:[39m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[39m  195, 201[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Case-mix adjustment models, clustering algorithms, feature engineering at scale |
[0m[49m[39m  196, 202[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon Redshift** | Analytical queries for provider metric aggregation, stores final results for dashboards |
[0m[49m[39m  197, 203[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Data lake for raw extracts, intermediate features, model artifacts, cluster results |
[0m[49m[39m  198, 204[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Glue** | ETL from source systems, data catalog for schema management |
[0m[49m[39m  199, 205[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon QuickSight** | Provider-facing dashboards with row-level security |
[0m[49m[39m  200, 206[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Step Functions** | Orchestrates the quarterly analysis pipeline end-to-end |
[0m[49m[39m  201, 207[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for all data at rest |
[0m[49m[39m  202, 208[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  203, 209[0m:[39m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[39m  204, 210[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  205, 211[0m:[39m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[39m  206, 212[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  207, 213[0m:[39m[49m **Step 1: Extract and aggregate provider metrics.** The first step pulls raw clinical data from your source systems and aggregates it to the provider level. For each provider, you calculate raw utilization metrics over your chosen time window (typically 12 months). This includes ordering rates, referral rates, prescribing patterns, cost metrics, and quality scores. The aggregation must be specialty-specific: you only compare providers within the same specialty. Skip this step and you have no data to analyze. Get the time window wrong and you either have too much noise (short window, small panels) or miss practice evolution (overly long window).
[0m[49m[39m  208, 214[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Before case-mix adjustment, validate input data: check record counts against expected volumes (alert if more than 20% deviation from prior quarter), verify all expected providers appear in the extract, check for temporal completeness (all 12 months of the analysis window have data), and validate HCC score distributions haven't shifted dramatically (which could indicate a coding change rather than real acuity change). Halt the pipeline and alert if any validation fails.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  209, 217[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  210, 218[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION aggregate_provider_metrics(time_window_months, min_panel_size):
[0m[49m[39m  211, 219[0m:[39m[49m     // Pull all encounters, orders, referrals, prescriptions, and outcomes
[0m[49m[39m  212, 220[0m:[39m[49m     // for the specified time window from the claims/EHR data warehouse.
[0m[49m[39m  213, 221[0m:[39m[49m     raw_data = query data warehouse for:
[0m[49m[39m  214, 222[0m:[39m[49m         - encounters by provider (with patient demographics and diagnoses)
[0m[49m[39m  215, 223[0m:[39m[49m         - lab/imaging orders by provider
[0m[49m[39m  216, 224[0m:[39m[49m         - referrals by provider (with destination specialty)
[0m[49m[39m  217, 225[0m:[39m[49m         - prescriptions by provider (with drug class, brand/generic)
[0m[49m[39m  218, 226[0m:[39m[49m         - quality measure numerators/denominators by provider
[0m[49m[39m  219, 227[0m:[39m[49m         - cost per episode by provider
[0m[49m[39m  220, 228[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  221, 229[0m:[39m[49m     // Aggregate to provider level. Each provider gets a vector of raw metrics.
[0m[49m[39m  222, 230[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each provider in raw_data:
[0m[49m[39m  223, 231[0m:[39m[49m         metrics[provider] = {
[0m[49m[39m  224, 232[0m:[39m[49m             panel_size:           count of unique patients seen,
[0m[49m[39m  225, 233[0m:[39m[49m             lab_rate:             labs ordered / patient / year,
[0m[49m[39m  226, 234[0m:[39m[49m             imaging_rate:         imaging studies / patient / year,
[0m[49m[39m  227, 235[0m:[39m[49m             mri_rate:             MRI specifically / patient / year,
[0m[49m[39m  228, 236[0m:[39m[49m             referral_rate:        referrals / patient / year,
[0m[49m[39m  229, 237[0m:[39m[49m             referral_breadth:     count of distinct specialists referred to,
[0m[49m[39m  230, 238[0m:[39m[49m             generic_rx_rate:      generic prescriptions / total prescriptions,
[0m[49m[39m  231, 239[0m:[39m[49m             opioid_rx_rate:       opioid prescriptions / total prescriptions,
[0m[49m[39m  232, 240[0m:[39m[49m             avg_cost_per_patient: total attributed cost / panel size,
[0m[49m[39m  233, 241[0m:[39m[49m             ed_rate:              ED visits among panel / panel size,
[0m[49m[39m  234, 242[0m:[39m[49m             readmit_rate:         30-day readmissions / discharges,
[0m[49m[39m  235, 243[0m:[39m[49m             quality_composite:    average quality measure performance (0-100),
[0m[49m[39m  236, 244[0m:[39m[49m             specialty:            provider's specialty code
[0m[49m[39m  237, 245[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  238, 246[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  239, 247[0m:[39m[49m     // Filter out providers with panels too small for stable estimates.
[0m[49m[39m  240, 248[0m:[39m[49m     // Small panels produce noisy metrics that distort clustering.
[0m[49m[39m  241, 249[0m:[39m[49m     filtered = remove providers where panel_size < min_panel_size
[0m[49m[39m  242, 250[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  243, 251[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN filtered metrics grouped by specialty
[0m[49m[39m  244, 252[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  245, 253[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  246, 254[0m:[39m[49m **Step 2: Case-mix adjustment.** This is the critical step that separates practice style from patient complexity. For each metric, you build a model that predicts the expected value based on the provider's patient panel characteristics. The difference between observed and expected is the provider's practice style signal. Without this step, you're just measuring which providers have sicker patients, not which providers practice differently. The adjustment model uses patient-level features (age, sex, HCC risk scores, chronic condition count, prior utilization) to predict expected utilization at the provider level.
[0m[49m[39m  247, 255[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  248, 256[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  249, 257[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION case_mix_adjust(provider_metrics, patient_data):
[0m[49m[39m  250, 258[0m:[39m[49m     // For each utilization metric, build a regression model predicting
[0m[49m[39m  251, 259[0m:[39m[49m     // expected values from patient characteristics.
[0m[49m[39m  252, 260[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  253, 261[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each metric in [lab_rate, imaging_rate, referral_rate, avg_cost, ...]:
[0m[49m[39m  254, 262[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  255, 263[0m:[39m[49m         // Build patient-level features for the adjustment model.
[0m[49m[39m  256, 264[0m:[39m[49m         // These represent the "difficulty" of each provider's panel.
[0m[49m[39m  257, 265[0m:[39m[49m         panel_features = FOR each provider:
[0m[49m[39m  258, 266[0m:[39m[49m             average HCC risk score of their patients,
[0m[49m[39m  259, 267[0m:[39m[49m             average age of their patients,
[0m[49m[39m  260, 268[0m:[39m[49m             percent female,
[0m[49m[39m  261, 269[0m:[39m[49m             average chronic condition count,
[0m[49m[39m  262, 270[0m:[39m[49m             percent dual-eligible (Medicare + Medicaid),
[0m[49m[39m  263, 271[0m:[39m[49m             average prior-year utilization of their patients
[0m[49m[39m  264, 272[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  265, 273[0m:[39m[49m         // Train a regression model: metric = f(panel_features)
[0m[49m[39m  266, 274[0m:[39m[49m         // This learns what utilization you'd EXPECT given the patient mix.
[0m[49m[39m  267, 275[0m:[39m[49m         model = train regression on (panel_features -> observed metric values)
[0m[49m[39m  268, 276[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  269, 277[0m:[39m[49m         // Calculate expected value for each provider given their panel.
[0m[49m[39m  270, 278[0m:[39m[49m         FOR each provider:
[0m[49m[39m  271, 279[0m:[39m[49m             expected = model.predict(provider's panel_features)
[0m[49m[39m  272, 280[0m:[39m[49m             
[0m[49m[39m  273, 281[0m:[39m[49m             // The O/E ratio isolates practice style from case mix.
[0m[49m[39m  274, 282[0m:[39m[49m             // O/E = 1.0 means "exactly as expected given your patients"
[0m[49m[39m  275, 283[0m:[39m[49m             // O/E = 1.3 means "30% more than expected" (practice style signal)
[0m[49m[39m  276, 284[0m:[39m[49m             provider.adjusted[metric] = provider.observed[metric] / expected
[0m[49m[39m  277, 285[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  278, 286[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN adjusted provider metrics (O/E ratios for each metric)
[0m[49m[39m  279, 287[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  280, 288[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  281, 289[0m:[39m[49m **Step 3: Feature engineering and normalization.** The adjusted metrics need preparation before clustering. This step normalizes features to comparable scales, handles any remaining outliers, and optionally reduces dimensionality. Providers with extreme O/E ratios (say, 5x expected on imaging) can distort cluster centroids, so winsorization (capping at the 95th percentile) is common. If you have 20+ metrics, PCA reduction to 5-8 components helps the clustering algorithm find cleaner structure without overfitting to noise in individual metrics.
[0m[49m[39m  282, 290[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  283, 291[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  284, 292[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION prepare_features(adjusted_metrics, n_components):
[0m[49m[39m  285, 293[0m:[39m[49m     // Normalize each adjusted metric to zero mean, unit variance.
[0m[49m[39m  286, 294[0m:[39m[49m     // This prevents metrics with larger numeric ranges from
[0m[49m[39m  287, 295[0m:[39m[49m     // dominating the distance calculations in clustering.
[0m[49m[39m  288, 296[0m:[39m[49m     normalized = z_score_normalize(adjusted_metrics)
[0m[49m[39m  289, 297[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  290, 298[0m:[39m[49m     // Winsorize extreme values to prevent outliers from distorting clusters.
[0m[49m[39m  291, 299[0m:[39m[49m     // Cap at 2.5 standard deviations (roughly the 99th percentile).
[0m[49m[39m  292, 300[0m:[39m[49m     // A provider with an O/E of 5.0 on imaging is interesting but shouldn't
[0m[49m[39m  293, 301[0m:[39m[49m     // pull an entire cluster centroid toward their extreme value.
[0m[49m[39m  294, 302[0m:[39m[49m     winsorized = cap values at +/- 2.5 standard deviations
[0m[49m[39m  295, 303[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  296, 304[0m:[39m[49m     // Optional: reduce dimensionality if feature count is high.
[0m[49m[39m  297, 305[0m:[39m[49m     // PCA finds the directions of maximum variance in the data.
[0m[49m[39m  298, 306[0m:[39m[49m     // Clustering in PCA space is more stable and less prone to noise.
[0m[49m[39m  299, 307[0m:[39m[49m     IF number of features > 10:
[0m[49m[39m  300, 308[0m:[39m[49m         reduced = PCA(winsorized, n_components=n_components)
[0m[49m[39m  301, 309[0m:[39m[49m         // Retain enough components to explain 85-90% of variance.
[0m[49m[39m  302, 310[0m:[39m[49m         // Record the component loadings for interpretation later.
[0m[49m[39m  303, 311[0m:[39m[49m         loadings = PCA component loadings (which original metrics contribute to each component)
[0m[49m[39m  304, 312[0m:[39m[49m     ELSE:
[0m[49m[39m  305, 313[0m:[39m[49m         reduced = winsorized
[0m[49m[39m  306, 314[0m:[39m[49m         loadings = identity (each feature is its own "component")
[0m[49m[39m  307, 315[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  308, 316[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN reduced feature matrix, loadings
[0m[49m[39m  309, 317[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  310, 318[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  311, 319[0m:[39m[49m **Step 4: Clustering.** Apply the clustering algorithm to the prepared feature matrix. This step identifies groups of providers with similar practice styles. The choice of K (number of clusters) should balance statistical separation with operational utility. Run multiple values of K and evaluate both quantitative metrics (silhouette score) and qualitative interpretability. A medical director needs to be able to explain what each cluster represents in plain clinical language.
[0m[49m[39m  312, 320[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  313, 321[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  314, 322[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION cluster_providers(feature_matrix, k_range):
[0m[49m[39m  315, 323[0m:[39m[49m     // Try multiple values of K to find the best segmentation.
[0m[49m[39m  316, 324[0m:[39m[49m     // k_range is typically [3, 4, 5, 6] for provider profiling.
[0m[49m[39m  317, 325[0m:[39m[49m     results = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  318, 326[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  319, 327[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each k in k_range:
[0m[49m[39m  320, 328[0m:[39m[49m         // Run K-Means (or GMM for soft assignments).
[0m[49m[39m  321, 329[0m:[39m[49m         model = fit KMeans(n_clusters=k) on feature_matrix
[0m[49m[39m  322, 330[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  323, 331[0m:[39m[49m         // Calculate silhouette score: measures how well-separated clusters are.
[0m[49m[39m  324, 332[0m:[39m[49m         // Range is -1 to 1. Above 0.3 is decent. Above 0.5 is good.
[0m[49m[39m  325, 333[0m:[39m[49m         silhouette = calculate silhouette score for this clustering
[0m[49m[39m  326, 334[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  327, 335[0m:[39m[49m         // Calculate within-cluster sum of squares (inertia).
[0m[49m[39m  328, 336[0m:[39m[49m         // Lower is better, but always decreases with more clusters.
[0m[49m[39m  329, 337[0m:[39m[49m         inertia = model.inertia
[0m[49m[39m  330, 338[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  331, 339[0m:[39m[49m         // Store results for comparison.
[0m[49m[39m  332, 340[0m:[39m[49m         results.append({k, model, silhouette, inertia})
[0m[49m[39m  333, 341[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  334, 342[0m:[39m[49m     // Select K based on silhouette score AND interpretability.
[0m[49m[39m  335, 343[0m:[39m[49m     // The "best" K statistically may not be the most useful operationally.
[0m[49m[39m  336, 344[0m:[39m[49m     best_model = select model with best silhouette (or clinical preference)
[0m[49m[39m  337, 345[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  338, 346[0m:[39m[49m     // Assign each provider to their cluster.
[0m[49m[39m  339, 347[0m:[39m[49m     assignments = best_model.predict(feature_matrix)
[0m[49m[39m  340, 348[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  341, 349[0m:[39m[49m     // For GMM: also get soft assignments (probability per cluster).
[0m[49m[39m  342, 350[0m:[39m[49m     // "Dr. Smith is 72% Cluster A, 28% Cluster B" is more nuanced
[0m[49m[39m  343, 351[0m:[39m[49m     // than a hard assignment and useful for borderline cases.
[0m[49m[39m  344, 352[0m:[39m[49m     probabilities = best_model.predict_proba(feature_matrix)  // GMM only
[0m[49m[39m  345, 353[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  346, 354[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN assignments, probabilities, best_model
[0m[49m[39m  347, 355[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  348, 356[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  349, 357[0m:[39m[49m **Step 5: Cluster interpretation and labeling.** Raw cluster numbers mean nothing to clinicians. This step characterizes each cluster by examining which metrics are most distinctive (highest or lowest relative to the overall mean). The goal is a plain-language label that a medical director can use in conversation: "conservative/efficient," "thorough/resource-intensive," "procedure-oriented," etc. These labels should be developed collaboratively with clinical leadership, not assigned unilaterally by the analytics team.
[0m[49m[39m  350, 358[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  351, 359[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  352, 360[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION interpret_clusters(assignments, original_metrics, loadings):
[0m[49m[39m  353, 361[0m:[39m[49m     // For each cluster, calculate the mean of each original (adjusted) metric.
[0m[49m[39m  354, 362[0m:[39m[49m     // Compare to the overall population mean.
[0m[49m[39m  355, 363[0m:[39m[49m     cluster_profiles = empty map
[0m[49m[39m  356, 364[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  357, 365[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each cluster_id in unique(assignments):
[0m[49m[39m  358, 366[0m:[39m[49m         cluster_members = providers where assignment == cluster_id
[0m[49m[39m  359, 367[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  360, 368[0m:[39m[49m         // Calculate mean of each metric for this cluster.
[0m[49m[39m  361, 369[0m:[39m[49m         cluster_means = mean of each metric across cluster_members
[0m[49m[39m  362, 370[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  363, 371[0m:[39m[49m         // Calculate z-score relative to overall population.
[0m[49m[39m  364, 372[0m:[39m[49m         // Positive z-score = this cluster is ABOVE average on this metric.
[0m[49m[39m  365, 373[0m:[39m[49m         // Negative z-score = this cluster is BELOW average.
[0m[49m[39m  366, 374[0m:[39m[49m         relative_profile = (cluster_means - overall_means) / overall_std
[0m[49m[39m  367, 375[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  368, 376[0m:[39m[49m         // Identify the 3-5 most distinctive features for this cluster.
[0m[49m[39m  369, 377[0m:[39m[49m         // These are the features with the largest absolute z-scores.
[0m[49m[39m  370, 378[0m:[39m[49m         distinctive_features = top 5 features by absolute z-score
[0m[49m[39m  371, 379[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  372, 380[0m:[39m[49m         cluster_profiles[cluster_id] = {
[0m[49m[39m  373, 381[0m:[39m[49m             size:                 count of providers in this cluster,
[0m[49m[39m  374, 382[0m:[39m[49m             distinctive_features: distinctive_features,
[0m[49m[39m  375, 383[0m:[39m[49m             relative_profile:     relative_profile,
[0m[49m[39m  376, 384[0m:[39m[49m             suggested_label:      generate label from distinctive features
[0m[49m[39m  377, 385[0m:[39m[49m             // e.g., high imaging + high referral + high cost = "thorough/resource-intensive"
[0m[49m[39m  378, 386[0m:[39m[49m             // e.g., low imaging + low referral + low cost + avg quality = "conservative/efficient"
[0m[49m[39m  379, 387[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  380, 388[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  381, 389[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN cluster_profiles
[0m[49m[39m  382, 390[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  383, 391[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  384, 392[0m:[39m[49m **Step 6: Generate provider reports.** The final step produces individual provider reports and aggregate dashboards. Each provider sees their cluster assignment, how their metrics compare to their cluster peers and to the overall specialty, and which specific metrics are most distinctive about their practice style. Medical directors see the full landscape: cluster sizes, characteristics, outcome correlations, and individual provider positions. Row-level security ensures providers see peer comparisons in aggregate but cannot identify individual peers.
[0m[49m[39m  385, 393[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  386, 394[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  387, 395[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION generate_reports(assignments, profiles, provider_metrics):
[0m[49m[39m  388, 396[0m:[39m[49m     // Individual provider report.
[0m[49m[39m  389, 397[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each provider:
[0m[49m[39m  390, 398[0m:[39m[49m         report = {
[0m[49m[39m  391, 399[0m:[39m[49m             provider_id:       provider identifier,
[0m[49m[39m  392, 400[0m:[39m[49m             specialty:         provider's specialty,
[0m[49m[39m  393, 401[0m:[39m[49m             cluster:           assigned cluster label (e.g., "Conservative/Efficient"),
[0m[49m[39m  394, 402[0m:[39m[49m             cluster_confidence: probability of cluster membership (from GMM),
[0m[49m[39m  395, 403[0m:[39m[49m             
[0m[49m[39m  396, 404[0m:[39m[49m             // Show where this provider sits relative to peers.
[0m[49m[39m  397, 405[0m:[39m[49m             peer_comparison: FOR each metric:
[0m[49m[39m  398, 406[0m:[39m[49m                 {
[0m[49m[39m  399, 407[0m:[39m[49m                     metric_name:    metric label,
[0m[49m[39m  400, 408[0m:[39m[49m                     provider_value: this provider's adjusted value,
[0m[49m[39m  401, 409[0m:[39m[49m                     cluster_mean:   mean for their cluster,
[0m[49m[39m  402, 410[0m:[39m[49m                     specialty_mean: mean for all providers in this specialty,
[0m[49m[39m  403, 411[0m:[39m[49m                     percentile:     where they fall in the specialty distribution
[0m[49m[39m  404, 412[0m:[39m[49m                 },
[0m[49m[39m  405, 413[0m:[39m[49m             
[0m[49m[39m  406, 414[0m:[39m[49m             // Highlight the 3 metrics most responsible for their cluster assignment.
[0m[49m[39m  407, 415[0m:[39m[49m             key_drivers: top 3 metrics by contribution to cluster assignment,
[0m[49m[39m  408, 416[0m:[39m[49m             
[0m[49m[39m  409, 417[0m:[39m[49m             // Outcome context: how does their cluster perform on outcomes?
[0m[49m[39m  410, 418[0m:[39m[49m             cluster_outcomes: {
[0m[49m[39m  411, 419[0m:[39m[49m                 avg_quality_score:  cluster average quality composite,
[0m[49m[39m  412, 420[0m:[39m[49m                 avg_cost:           cluster average cost per patient,
[0m[49m[39m  413, 421[0m:[39m[49m                 avg_readmit_rate:   cluster average readmission rate
[0m[49m[39m  414, 422[0m:[39m[49m             }
[0m[49m[39m  415, 423[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  416, 424[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  417, 425[0m:[39m[49m         write report to storage
[0m[49m[39m  418, 426[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  419, 427[0m:[39m[49m     // Aggregate dashboard for medical directors.
[0m[49m[39m  420, 428[0m:[39m[49m     dashboard = {
[0m[49m[39m  421, 429[0m:[39m[49m         cluster_summary:    size and characteristics of each cluster,
[0m[49m[39m  422, 430[0m:[39m[49m         outcome_by_cluster: quality and cost metrics by cluster,
[0m[49m[39m  423, 431[0m:[39m[49m         outlier_list:       providers far from any cluster centroid,
[0m[49m[39m  424, 432[0m:[39m[49m         trend:              how cluster assignments changed from last quarter
[0m[49m[39m  425, 433[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  426, 434[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  427, 435[0m:[39m[49m     write dashboard to storage
[0m[49m[39m  428, 436[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN reports, dashboard
[0m[49m[39m  429, 437[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  430, 438[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  431, 439[0m:[39m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter06.05-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[39m  432, 440[0m:[39m[49m 
